# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: continual-improvement-process
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:continual-improvement-process/benchmarking] Benchmarking is used to measure performance using a specific indicator (cost per unit of measure, productivity per unit of measure, cycle time of x per unit of measure or defects per unit of measure) resulting in a metric of performance that is then compared to others.
[src:continual-improvement-process/benchmarking] Also referred to as "best practice benchmarking" or "process benchmarking," this process is used in management, in which organizations evaluate various aspects of their processes in relation to the processes of best-practice companies, usually within a peer group defined for comparison.
[src:continual-improvement-process/benchmarking] This allows organizations to develop plans to make improvements or adopt specific best practices, usually with the aim of increasing some aspect of performance.
[src:continual-improvement-process/benchmarking] Benchmarking may be a one-off event, but it is often treated as a continuous process in which organizations continually seek to improve their practices.
[src:continual-improvement-process/benchmarking] In project management benchmarking can also support the selection, planning and delivery of projects.
[src:continual-improvement-process/benchmarking] In the process of best practice benchmarking, management identifies the best firms in their industry, or in another industry where similar processes exist, and compares the results and processes of those studied (the "targets") to one's own results and processes.
[src:continual-improvement-process/benchmarking] In this way, they learn how well the targets perform and, more importantly, the business processes that explain why these firms are successful.
[src:continual-improvement-process/benchmarking] According to National Council on Measurement in Education, benchmark assessments are short assessments used by teachers at various times throughout the school year to monitor student progress in some area of the school curriculum.
[src:continual-improvement-process/benchmarking] These also are known as interim government.
[src:continual-improvement-process/benchmarking] In 1994, one of the first technical journals named *Benchmarking* was published.
[src:continual-improvement-process/benchmarking] An early example of benchmarking is the Auerbach Corporation's Standard EDP Reports, which were first developed in 1962.
[src:continual-improvement-process/benchmarking] In 2008, a comprehensive survey on benchmarking was commissioned by The Global Benchmarking Network, a network of benchmarking centres representing 22 countries.
[src:continual-improvement-process/benchmarking] The tools that are likely to increase in popularity the most over the next three years are Performance Benchmarking, Informal Benchmarking, SWOT, and Best Practice Benchmarking.
[src:continual-improvement-process/benchmarking] Over 60% of organizations that are not currently using these tools indicated they are likely to use them in the next three years.
[src:continual-improvement-process/benchmarking] Benchmarking mainly depends on SWOT analysis and will also be using in future for almost 4–5 years.
[src:continual-improvement-process/benchmarking] There is no single benchmarking process that has been universally adopted.
[src:continual-improvement-process/benchmarking] The wide appeal and acceptance of benchmarking has led to the emergence of benchmarking methodologies.
[src:continual-improvement-process/benchmarking] One seminal book is Boxwell's *Benchmarking for Competitive Advantage* (1994).
[src:continual-improvement-process/benchmarking] The first book on benchmarking, written and published by Kaiser Associates, is a practical guide and offers a seven-step approach.
[src:continual-improvement-process/benchmarking] Robert Camp (who wrote one of the earliest books on benchmarking in 1989) developed a 12-stage approach to benchmarking.
[src:continual-improvement-process/benchmarking] The cost of benchmarking can substantially be reduced through utilizing the many internet resources that have sprung up over the last few years.
[src:continual-improvement-process/benchmarking] These aim to capture benchmarks and best practices from organizations, business sectors and countries to make the benchmarking process much quicker and cheaper.
[src:continual-improvement-process/benchmarking] The technique initially used to compare existing corporate strategies with a view to achieving the best possible performance in new situations (see above), has recently been extended to the comparison of technical products.
[src:continual-improvement-process/benchmarking] This process is usually referred to as "technical benchmarking" or "product benchmarking".
[src:continual-improvement-process/benchmarking] Its use is well-developed within the automotive industry ("automotive benchmarking"), where it is vital to design products that match precise user expectations, at minimal cost, by applying the best technologies available worldwide.
[src:continual-improvement-process/benchmarking] Data is obtained by fully disassembling existing cars and their systems.
[src:continual-improvement-process/benchmarking] Such analyses were initially carried out in-house by car makers and their suppliers.
[src:continual-improvement-process/benchmarking] However, as these analyses are expensive, they are increasingly being outsourced to companies who specialize in this area.
[src:continual-improvement-process/benchmarking] Outsourcing has enabled a drastic decrease in costs for each company (by cost sharing) and the development of efficient tools (standards, software).
[src:continual-improvement-process/benchmarking] Benchmarking can be internal (comparing performance between different groups or teams within an organization) or external (comparing performance with companies in a specific industry or across industries).
[src:continual-improvement-process/benchmarking] Benchmarking software can be used to organize large and complex amounts of information.
[src:continual-improvement-process/benchmarking] Software packages can extend the concept of benchmarking and competitive analysis by allowing individuals to handle such large and complex amounts or strategies.
[src:continual-improvement-process/benchmarking] Such tools support different types of benchmarking (see above) and can reduce the above costs significantly.
[src:continual-improvement-process/benchmarking] The emerging technology of benchmarking engines automates the process of turning data into noteworthy comparative insights, sometimes even expressing those insights in English sentences.
[src:continual-improvement-process/benchmarking] Another approach to making comparisons involves using more aggregative cost or production information to identify strong and weak performing units.
[src:continual-improvement-process/benchmarking] The two most common forms of quantitative analysis used in metric benchmarking are data envelopment analysis (DEA) and regression analysis.
[src:continual-improvement-process/benchmarking] DEA estimates the cost level an efficient firm should be able to achieve in a particular market.
[src:continual-improvement-process/benchmarking] In infrastructure regulation, DEA can be used to reward companies/operators whose costs are near the efficient frontier with additional profits.
[src:continual-improvement-process/benchmarking] Regression analysis estimates what the average firm should be able to achieve.
[src:continual-improvement-process/benchmarking] With regression analysis, firms that performed better than average can be rewarded while firms that performed worse than average can be penalized.
[src:continual-improvement-process/benchmarking] Such benchmarking studies are used to create yardstick comparisons, allowing outsiders to evaluate the performance of operators in an industry.
[src:continual-improvement-process/benchmarking] Advanced statistical techniques, including stochastic frontier analysis, have been used to identify high and weak performers in industries, including applications to schools, hospitals, water utilities, and electric utilities.
[src:continual-improvement-process/benchmarking] One of the biggest challenges in metric benchmarking is the variety of metric definitions used among companies or divisions.
[src:continual-improvement-process/benchmarking] Definitions may change over time within the same organization due to changes in leadership and priorities.
[src:continual-improvement-process/benchmarking] The most useful comparisons can be made when metric definitions are consistent across the units being compared and remain unchanged over time, allowing improvements to be measured accurately.
[src:continual-improvement-process/bsi-group] The **British Standards Institution** (**BSI**) is the national standards body of the United Kingdom.
[src:continual-improvement-process/bsi-group] BSI produces technical standards on a wide range of products and services and also supplies standards certification services for business and personnel.
[src:continual-improvement-process/bsi-group] BSI was founded as the Engineering Standards Committee in London in 1901.
[src:continual-improvement-process/bsi-group] It subsequently extended its standardization work and became the British Engineering Standards Association in 1918, adopting the name British Standards Institution in 1931 after receiving a Royal Charter in 1929.
[src:continual-improvement-process/bsi-group] In 1998, a revision of the Charter enabled the organization to diversify and acquire other businesses, and the trading name was changed to BSI Group.
[src:continual-improvement-process/bsi-group] The Group now operates in 195 countries.
[src:continual-improvement-process/bsi-group] The core business remains standards and standards related services, although the majority of the Group's revenue comes from management systems assessment and certification work.
[src:continual-improvement-process/bsi-group] In 2021, BSI appointed its first female chief executive officer, Susan Taylor Martin.
[src:continual-improvement-process/bsi-group] BSI produces British Standards, and, as the UK's National Standards Body, is also responsible for the UK publication, in English, of international and European standards.
[src:continual-improvement-process/bsi-group] BSI is obliged to adopt and publish all European Standards as identical British Standards (prefixed BS EN) and to withdraw pre-existing British Standards that are in conflict.
[src:continual-improvement-process/bsi-group] However, it has the option to adopt and publish international standards (prefixed BS ISO or BS IEC).
[src:continual-improvement-process/bsi-group] In response to commercial demands, BSI also produces commissioned standards products such as Publicly Available Specifications (PASs), Private Standards and Business Information Publications.
[src:continual-improvement-process/bsi-group] These products are commissioned by individual organizations and trade associations to meet their needs for standardized specifications, guidelines, codes of practice etc.
[src:continual-improvement-process/bsi-group] Because they are not subject to the same consultation and consensus requirements as formal standards, the lead time is shorter.
[src:continual-improvement-process/bsi-group] BSI also publishes standards-related books, CD-ROMs, subscription and web-based products as well as providing training on standards-related issues.
[src:continual-improvement-process/bsi-group] With 80,000 clients, BSI is one of the world's largest certification bodies.
[src:continual-improvement-process/bsi-group] It audits and provides certification to companies worldwide who implement management systems standards.
[src:continual-improvement-process/bsi-group] BSI also runs training courses that cover the implementation and auditing requirements of national and international management systems standards.
[src:continual-improvement-process/bsi-group] BSI's best known product in the UK is the Kitemark, a registered certification mark first used in 1903.
[src:continual-improvement-process/bsi-group] The Kitemark – which is recognized by 82% of UK adults – signifies products or services which have been assessed and tested as meeting the requirements of the related specification or standard within a Kitemark scheme.
[src:continual-improvement-process/bsi-group] BSI also conducts testing of products for a range of certifications, including for CE marking.
[src:continual-improvement-process/bsi-group] CE marking must be applied to a wide range of products intended for sale in the European Economic Area.
[src:continual-improvement-process/bsi-group] Frequently, manufacturers or importers need a third-party certification of their product from an accredited or 'Notified' body.
[src:continual-improvement-process/bsi-group] BSI holds Notified Body status for 15 EU Directives, including construction products, marine equipment, pressurized equipment and personal protective equipment.
[src:continual-improvement-process/bsi-group] BSI also conducts testing for manufacturers developing new products and has facilities to test across a wide range of sectors, including construction, fire safety, electrical and electronic and engineering products.
[src:continual-improvement-process/bsi-group] BSI provides regulatory and quality management reviews and product certification for medical device manufacturers in the Worldwide.
[src:continual-improvement-process/bsi-group] It is the market leader in the US, the world's biggest healthcare market.
[src:continual-improvement-process/bsi-group] In 2021, BSI Group, with support from the Construction Products Association, led the development of a product identification and traceability system known as *BSI Identify*.
[src:continual-improvement-process/bsi-group] The initiative responded to recommendations made by Dame Judith Hackitt following her review of building safety, which called for wider adoption of permanent product marking and consistent labelling systems to improve traceability across the built environment sector.
[src:continual-improvement-process/bsi-group] BSI Identify uses new Digital Object Identifier (DOI) technology "to deliver a unique, constant, and interoperable identifier", known as a BSI UPIN, "which can be assigned to products to help UK manufacturers to directly manage information about their products in the supply chain".
[src:continual-improvement-process/bsi-group] The aim of the BSI Identify programme is that "wherever you are with [a] product, you can take a snapshot of the QR code with your mobile device, and it will immediately take you to the product technical data sheet.
[src:continual-improvement-process/bsi-group] The BSI coat of arms was granted by the College of Arms in 1951.
[src:continual-improvement-process/business-process-management] As an approach, BPM treats processes as important organizational assets that must be understood, managed, and continuously improved in order to create and deliver value to clients or customers.
[src:continual-improvement-process/business-process-management] This approach closely resembles other total quality management or continual improvement process methodologies.
[src:continual-improvement-process/business-process-management] ISO 9000:2015 promotes the process approach to managing an organization.
[src:continual-improvement-process/business-process-management] BPM proponents also claim that this approach can be supported, or enabled, through technology.
[src:continual-improvement-process/business-process-management] Therefore, multiple BPM articles and scholars frequently discuss BPM from one of two viewpoints: people and/or technology.
[src:continual-improvement-process/business-process-management] BPM streamlines business processing by automating workflows; while RPA automates tasks by recording a set of repetitive activities performed by humans.
[src:continual-improvement-process/business-process-management] Organizations maximize their business automation leveraging both technologies to achieve better results.
[src:continual-improvement-process/business-process-management] Business process management (BPM) is a disciplined approach to identify, design, execute, document, measure, monitor, and control both automated and non-automated business processes to achieve consistent, targeted results aligned with an organization's strategic goals.
[src:continual-improvement-process/business-process-management] BPM involves the deliberate, collaborative and increasingly technology-aided definition, improvement, innovation, and management of end-to-end business processes that drive business results, create value, and enable an organization to meet its business objectives with more agility.
[src:continual-improvement-process/business-process-management] BPM enables an enterprise to align its business processes to its business strategy, leading to effective overall company performance through improvements of specific work activities either within a specific department, across the enterprise, or between organizations.
[src:continual-improvement-process/business-process-management] "the discipline of managing processes (rather than tasks) as the means for improving business performance outcomes and operational agility.
[src:continual-improvement-process/business-process-management] It is common to confuse BPM with a BPM suite (BPMS).
[src:continual-improvement-process/business-process-management] BPM is a professional discipline done by people, whereas a BPMS is a technological suite of tools designed to help the BPM professionals accomplish their goals.
[src:continual-improvement-process/business-process-management] BPM should also not be confused with an application or solution developed to support a particular process.
[src:continual-improvement-process/business-process-management] Suites and solutions represent ways of automating business processes, but automation is only one aspect of BPM.
[src:continual-improvement-process/business-process-management] Business process management has evolved from earlier management and quality movements, including total quality management and business process reengineering, into a broader organisational discipline concerned with the end-to-end governance, performance, and continuous improvement of processes.
[src:continual-improvement-process/business-process-management] Contemporary academic and professional literature commonly defines BPM not only as a set of modelling or automation techniques, but as a management approach that integrates process design, execution, monitoring, and optimisation with organisational strategy, governance, and information systems.
[src:continual-improvement-process/business-process-management] In this sense, BPM differs from isolated process improvement initiatives by emphasising sustained organisational capability, cross-functional coordination, and continuous improvement over time, rather than one-off redesign efforts.
[src:continual-improvement-process/business-process-management] It can be differentiated from program management in that program management is concerned with managing a group of inter-dependent projects.
[src:continual-improvement-process/business-process-management] From another viewpoint, process management includes program management.
[src:continual-improvement-process/business-process-management] In project management, process management is the use of a repeatable process to improve the outcome of the project.
[src:continual-improvement-process/business-process-management] A key distinction between process management and project management lies in repeatability and predictability.
[src:continual-improvement-process/business-process-management] If the structure and sequence of work are unique, then it is a project.
[src:continual-improvement-process/business-process-management] In business process management, a workflow can vary from case to case due to gateways, conditions, and business rules.
[src:continual-improvement-process/business-process-management] The key is predictability: no matter how many forks in the road, we know all of them in advance, and we understand the conditions for the process to take one route or another.
[src:continual-improvement-process/business-process-management] If this condition is met, we are dealing with a process.
[src:continual-improvement-process/business-process-management] The concept of business process may be as traditional as concepts of tasks, department, production, and outputs, arising from job shop scheduling problems in the early 20th century.
[src:continual-improvement-process/business-process-management] The management and improvement approach as of 2010, with formal definitions and technical modeling, has been around since the early 1990s (see business process modeling).
[src:continual-improvement-process/business-process-management] Note that the term "business process" is sometimes used by IT practitioners as synonymous with the management of middleware processes or with integrating application software tasks.
[src:continual-improvement-process/business-process-management] Although BPM initially focused on the automation of business processes through information technology, the discipline has evolved to encompass human-driven processes in which human interaction takes place in series or in parallel with automated tasks.
[src:continual-improvement-process/business-process-management] For example, workflow management systems can assign individual steps requiring deploying human intuition or judgment to relevant humans and other tasks in a workflow to a relevant automated system.
[src:continual-improvement-process/business-process-management] More recent variations such as "human interaction management" are concerned with the interaction between human workers performing a task.
[src:continual-improvement-process/business-process-management] As of 2010, technology has allowed the coupling of BPM with other methodologies, such as Six Sigma.
[src:continual-improvement-process/business-process-management] This brings with it the benefit of being able to simulate changes to business processes based on real-world data (not just on assumed knowledge).
[src:continual-improvement-process/business-process-management] Also, the coupling of BPM to industry methodologies allows users to continually streamline and optimize the process to ensure that it is tuned to its market need.
[src:continual-improvement-process/business-process-management] As of 2012 research on BPM has paid increasing attention to the compliance of business processes.
[src:continual-improvement-process/business-process-management] Although a key aspect of business processes is flexibility, as business processes continuously need to adapt to changes in the environment, compliance with business strategy, policies, and government regulations should also be ensured.
[src:continual-improvement-process/business-process-management] The compliance aspect in BPM is highly important for governmental organizations.
[src:continual-improvement-process/business-process-management] As of 2010 BPM approaches in a governmental context largely focus on operational processes and knowledge representation.
[src:continual-improvement-process/business-process-management] There have been a number of technical studies on operational business processes in the public and private sectors, but researchers rarely take legal compliance activities into account—for instance, the legal implementation processes in public-administration bodies.
[src:continual-improvement-process/business-process-management] Business process management activities can be arbitrarily grouped into categories such as design, modeling, execution, monitoring, and optimization.
[src:continual-improvement-process/business-process-management] Process design encompasses both the identification of existing processes and the design of "to-be" processes.
[src:continual-improvement-process/business-process-management] Areas of focus include representation of the process flow, the factors within it, alerts and notifications, escalations, standard operating procedures, service level agreements, and task hand-over mechanisms.
[src:continual-improvement-process/business-process-management] Whether or not existing processes are considered, the aim of this step is to ensure a correct and efficient new design.
[src:continual-improvement-process/business-process-management] The proposed improvement could be in human-to-human, human-to-system or system-to-system workflows, and might target regulatory, market, or competitive challenges faced by the businesses.
[src:continual-improvement-process/business-process-management] Existing processes and design of a new process for various applications must synchronize and not cause a major outage or process interruption.
[src:continual-improvement-process/business-process-management] Modeling takes the theoretical design and introduces combinations of variables (e.g., changes in rent or materials costs, which determine how the process might operate under different circumstances).
[src:continual-improvement-process/business-process-management] It may also involve running "what-if analysis"(Conditions-when, if, else) on the processes: *"What if I have 75% of resources to do the same task?"* *"What if I want to do the same job for 80% of the current cost?"*.
[src:continual-improvement-process/business-process-management] Business process execution is broadly about enacting a discovered and modeled business process.
[src:continual-improvement-process/business-process-management] Enacting a business process is done manually or automatically or with a combination of manual and automated business tasks.
[src:continual-improvement-process/business-process-management] Manual business processes are human-driven.
[src:continual-improvement-process/business-process-management] Automated business processes are software-driven.
[src:continual-improvement-process/business-process-management] Business process automation encompasses methods and software deployed for automating business processes.
[src:continual-improvement-process/business-process-management] Business process automation is performed and orchestrated at the business process layer or the consumer presentation layer of SOA Reference Architecture.
[src:continual-improvement-process/business-process-management] BPM software suites such as BPMS or iBPMS or low-code platforms are positioned at the business process layer.
[src:continual-improvement-process/business-process-management] While the emerging robotic process automation software performs business process automation at the presentation layer, therefore is considered non-invasive to and de-coupled from existing application systems.
[src:continual-improvement-process/business-process-management] One of the ways to automate processes is to develop or purchase an application that executes the required steps of the process; however, in practice, these applications rarely execute all the steps of the process accurately or completely.
[src:continual-improvement-process/business-process-management] Another approach is to use a combination of software and human intervention; however this approach is more complex, making the documentation process difficult.
[src:continual-improvement-process/business-process-management] In response to these problems, companies have developed software that defines the full business process (as developed in the process design activity) in a computer language that a computer can directly execute.
[src:continual-improvement-process/business-process-management] Process models can be run through execution engines that automate the processes directly from the model (e.g., calculating a repayment plan for a loan) or, when a step is too complex to automate, Business Process Modeling Notation (BPMN) provides front-end capability for human input.
[src:continual-improvement-process/business-process-management] Compared to either of the previous approaches, directly executing a process definition can be more straightforward and therefore easier to improve.
[src:continual-improvement-process/business-process-management] However, automating a process definition requires flexible and comprehensive infrastructure, which typically rules out implementing these systems in a legacy IT environment.
[src:continual-improvement-process/business-process-management] Business rules have been used by systems to provide definitions for governing behavior, and a business rule engine can be used to drive process execution and resolution.
[src:continual-improvement-process/business-process-management] Monitoring encompasses the tracking of individual processes, so that information on their state can be easily seen, and statistics on the performance of one or more processes can be provided.
[src:continual-improvement-process/business-process-management] An example of this tracking is being able to determine the state of a customer order *(e.g.* order arrived, awaiting delivery, invoice paid) so that problems in its operation can be identified and corrected.
[src:continual-improvement-process/business-process-management] In addition, this information can be used to work with customers and suppliers to improve their connected processes.
[src:continual-improvement-process/business-process-management] Examples are the generation of measures on how quickly a customer order is processed or how many orders were processed in the last month.
[src:continual-improvement-process/business-process-management] These measures tend to fit into three categories: cycle time, defect rate and productivity.
[src:continual-improvement-process/business-process-management] The degree of monitoring depends on what information the business wants to evaluate and analyze and how the business wants it monitored, in real-time, near real-time or ad hoc.
[src:continual-improvement-process/business-process-management] Here, business activity monitoring (BAM) extends and expands the monitoring tools generally provided by BPMS.
[src:continual-improvement-process/business-process-management] Process mining is a collection of methods and tools related to process monitoring.
[src:continual-improvement-process/business-process-management] The aim of process mining is to analyze event logs extracted through process monitoring and to compare them with an *a priori* process model.
[src:continual-improvement-process/business-process-management] Process mining allows process analysts to detect discrepancies between the actual process execution and the *a priori* model as well as to analyze bottlenecks.
[src:continual-improvement-process/business-process-management] Predictive business process monitoring concerns the application of data mining, machine learning, and other forecasting techniques to predict what is going to happen with running instances of a business process, allowing to make forecasts of future cycle time, compliance issues, etc.
[src:continual-improvement-process/business-process-management] Techniques for predictive business process monitoring include Support Vector Machines, Deep Learning approaches, and Random Forest.
[src:continual-improvement-process/business-process-management] Process optimization includes retrieving process performance information from modeling or monitoring phase; identifying the potential or actual bottlenecks and the potential opportunities for cost savings or other improvements; and then, applying those enhancements in the design of the process.
[src:continual-improvement-process/business-process-management] Process mining tools are able to discover critical activities and bottlenecks, creating greater business value.
[src:continual-improvement-process/business-process-management] Business process re-engineering (BPR) is a business management strategy originally pioneered in the early 1990s, focusing on the analysis and design of workflows and business processes within an organization.
[src:continual-improvement-process/business-process-management] BPR aims to help organizations fundamentally rethink how they do their work in order to improve customer service, cut operational costs, and become world-class competitors.
[src:continual-improvement-process/business-process-management] BPR seeks to help companies radically restructure their organizations by focusing on the ground-up design of their business processes.
[src:continual-improvement-process/business-process-management] According to early BPR proponent Thomas H.
[src:continual-improvement-process/business-process-management] Davenport (1990), a business process is a set of logically related tasks performed to achieve a defined business outcome.
[src:continual-improvement-process/business-process-management] Re-engineering emphasized a holistic focus on business objectives and how processes related to them, encouraging full-scale recreation of processes, rather than iterative optimization of sub-processes.
[src:continual-improvement-process/business-process-management] BPR is influenced by technological innovations as industry players replace old methods of business operations with cost-saving innovative technologies such as automation that can radically transform business operations.
[src:continual-improvement-process/business-process-management] Business process re-engineering is also known as business process redesign, business transformation, or business process change management.
[src:continual-improvement-process/business-process-management] A longitudinal multi-company study by Huising (2019) documents how experienced managers, after building wall-sized process maps, voluntarily transitioned into peripheral change-management positions in order to drive reforms from outside the traditional hierarchy.
[src:continual-improvement-process/business-process-management] A market has developed for enterprise software leveraging the business process management concepts to organize and automate processes.
[src:continual-improvement-process/business-process-management] The recent convergence of this software from distinct pieces such as business rules engine, business process modelling, business activity monitoring and Human Workflow has given birth to integrated business process management suites.
[src:continual-improvement-process/business-process-management] However, standalone integration-centric and document-centric offerings have matured into separate, standalone markets.
[src:continual-improvement-process/business-process-management] Rapid application development using no-code/low-code principles is becoming an ever prevalent feature of BPMS platforms.
[src:continual-improvement-process/business-process-management] RAD enables businesses to deploy applications more quickly and more cost effectively, while also offering improved change and version management.
[src:continual-improvement-process/business-process-management] Gartner notes that as businesses embrace these systems, their budgets rely less on the maintenance of existing systems and show more investment in growing and transforming them.
[src:continual-improvement-process/business-process-management] While the steps can be viewed as a cycle, economic or time constraints are likely to limit the process to only a few iterations.
[src:continual-improvement-process/business-process-management] This is often the case when an organization uses the approach for short to medium term objectives rather than trying to transform the organizational culture.
[src:continual-improvement-process/business-process-management] True iterations are only possible through the collaborative efforts of process participants.
[src:continual-improvement-process/business-process-management] In a majority of organizations, complexity requires enabling technology (see below) to support the process participants in these daily process management challenges.
[src:continual-improvement-process/business-process-management] To date, some organizations often start a BPM project or program with the objective of optimizing an area that has been identified as an area for improvement.
[src:continual-improvement-process/business-process-management] Currently, the international standards for the task have limited BPM to the application in the IT sector, and ISO/IEC 15944 covers the operational aspects of the business.
[src:continual-improvement-process/business-process-management] However, some corporations with the culture of best practices do use standard operating procedures to regulate their operational process.
[src:continual-improvement-process/business-process-management] Other standards are currently being worked upon to assist in BPM implementation (BPMN, enterprise architecture, Business Motivation Model).
[src:continual-improvement-process/business-process-management] BPM is now considered a critical component of operational intelligence (OI) solutions to deliver real-time, actionable information.
[src:continual-improvement-process/business-process-management] This real-time information can be acted upon in a variety of ways – alerts can be sent or executive decisions can be made using real-time dashboards.
[src:continual-improvement-process/business-process-management] OI solutions use real-time information to take automated action based on pre-defined rules so that security measures and or exception management processes can be initiated.
[src:continual-improvement-process/business-process-management] Validation of BPMS is another technical issue that vendors and users must be aware of, if regulatory compliance is mandatory.
[src:continual-improvement-process/business-process-management] The validation task could be performed either by an authenticated third party or by the users themselves.
[src:continual-improvement-process/business-process-management] Either way, validation documentation must be generated.
[src:continual-improvement-process/business-process-management] The validation document usually can either be published officially or retained by users.
[src:continual-improvement-process/business-process-management] According to Gartner, 20% of all the "shadow business processes" are supported by BPM cloud platforms.
[src:continual-improvement-process/business-process-management] Gartner refers to all the hidden organizational processes that are supported by IT departments as part of legacy business processes such as Excel spreadsheets, routing of emails using rules, phone calls routing, etc.
[src:continual-improvement-process/business-process-management] These can, of course also be replaced by other technologies such as workflow and smart form software.
[src:continual-improvement-process/business-process-management] The benefits of using cloud BPM services include removing the need and cost of maintaining specialized technical skill sets in-house and reducing distractions from an enterprise's main focus.
[src:continual-improvement-process/business-process-management] It offers controlled IT budgeting and enables geographical mobility..
[src:continual-improvement-process/business-process-management] The emerging Internet of Things presents challenges for managing and controlling the flow of information across large numbers of connected devices.
[src:continual-improvement-process/business-process-management] To address these challenges, approaches such as BPM Everywhere have been proposed, combining traditional business process management techniques with additional capabilities designed to support the coordination and automation of distributed devices.
[src:continual-improvement-process/continual-improvement-process] A **continual improvement process**, also often called a **continuous improvement process** (abbreviated as **CIP** or **CI**), is an ongoing effort to improve products, services, or processes.
[src:continual-improvement-process/continual-improvement-process] These efforts can seek "incremental" improvement over time or "breakthrough" improvement all at once.
[src:continual-improvement-process/continual-improvement-process] Delivery (customer valued) processes are constantly evaluated and improved in the light of their efficiency, effectiveness and flexibility.
[src:continual-improvement-process/continual-improvement-process] Some see continual improvement processes as a meta-process for most management systems (such as business process management, quality management, project management, and program management).
[src:continual-improvement-process/continual-improvement-process] Edwards Deming, a pioneer of the field, saw it as part of the 'system' whereby feedback from the process and customer were evaluated against organisational goals.
[src:continual-improvement-process/continual-improvement-process] The fact that it can be called a management process does not mean that it needs to be executed by 'management'; but rather merely that it makes decisions about the implementation of the delivery process and the design of the delivery process itself.
[src:continual-improvement-process/continual-improvement-process] A broader definition is that of the Institute of Quality Assurance who defined "continuous improvement as a gradual never-ending change which is: '... focused on increasing the effectiveness and/or efficiency of an organisation to fulfil its policy and objectives.
[src:continual-improvement-process/continual-improvement-process] It is not limited to quality initiatives.
[src:continual-improvement-process/continual-improvement-process] Improvement in business strategy, business results, customer, employee and supplier relationships can be subject to continual improvement.
[src:continual-improvement-process/continual-improvement-process] Some successful implementations use the approach known as kaizen (the translation of *kai* ('change') *zen* ('good') is 'improvement').
[src:continual-improvement-process/continual-improvement-process] The elements above are the more tactical elements of continual improvement processes.
[src:continual-improvement-process/continual-improvement-process] The more strategic elements include deciding how to increase the value of the delivery process output to the customer (effectiveness) and how much flexibility is valuable in the process to meet changing needs.
[src:continual-improvement-process/continual-improvement-process] The PDCA (plan, do, check, act) or (plan, do, check, adjust) cycle supports continuous improvement and kaizen.
[src:continual-improvement-process/continual-improvement-process] It provides a process for improvement which can be used since the early design (planning) stage of any process, system, product or service.
[src:continual-improvement-process/continual-improvement-process] The PDSA (plan, do, study, act) cycle is often credited to W.
[src:continual-improvement-process/continual-improvement-process] Edwards Deming and often called the Deming cycle though W.
[src:continual-improvement-process/continual-improvement-process] Edwards Deming referred to it as the Shewhart cycle.
[src:continual-improvement-process/continual-improvement-process] Shewhart back in the 1920s was working at Western Electric Company with W.
[src:continual-improvement-process/continual-improvement-process] Shewhart took the standard academic scientific method of inductive and deductive thinking, used in hypothesis testing, and converted it to a simple notion.
[src:continual-improvement-process/continual-improvement-process] When one does something, they plan it, do it, study it, and act on its results – the PDSA cycle.
[src:continual-improvement-process/continual-improvement-process] This was a far simpler notion to use and inform the shop floor of Western Electric while building telephones, where many workers would not and could not understand the scientific method.
[src:continual-improvement-process/continual-improvement-process] In fact, the PDSA notion could easily be applied to everyday activities such as driving a car to work.
[src:continual-improvement-process/continual-improvement-process] Thus, the PDSA cycle was very easy to relate to by Western's workforce and gained the buy-in needed.
[src:continual-improvement-process/continual-improvement-process] The continual improvement process concept is also used in environmental management systems (EMS), such as ISO 14000 and EMAS.
[src:continual-improvement-process/continual-improvement-process] The term "continual improvement", not "continuous improvement", is used in ISO 14000, and is understood to refer to an ongoing series of small or large-scale improvements which are each done discretely, i.e. in a step-wise fashion.
[src:continual-improvement-process/continual-improvement-process] Several differences exist between the CIP concept as it is applied in quality management and environmental management.
[src:continual-improvement-process/continual-improvement-process] Continual improvement in environmental management systems aims to improve the natural consequences of products and activities, not the products and activities as such.
[src:continual-improvement-process/continual-improvement-process] Secondly, there is no client-orientation in EMS-related continual improvement processes.
[src:continual-improvement-process/continual-improvement-process] Also, continual improvement processes in environmental management systems is not limited to small, incremental improvements as in kaizen, it also includes innovations of any scale.
[src:continual-improvement-process/continual-improvement-process] In the late 1990s, the developers of the ISO 9001:2000 standard—which addressed quality management systems and principles—debated whether or not to update the use of the word *continuous* to *continual*.
[src:continual-improvement-process/continual-improvement-process] ISO Technical Committee 176 and regulatory representatives ultimately decided that "continuous was unenforceable because it meant an organization had to improve minute by minute, whereas, continual improvement meant step-wise improvement or improvement in segments".
[src:continual-improvement-process/continual-improvement-process] The committee reportedly did not base the change on dictionary definitions or the standard's vocabulary.
[src:continual-improvement-process/continual-improvement-process] This change ran contrary to the common usage of *continuous* in the standard and other prior business management documentation.
[src:continual-improvement-process/continual-improvement-process] The concept of continual improvement is the core of the British Standards Institution's 2019 publication: BS 8624 Guide to Continual improvement: Methods for quantification.
[src:continual-improvement-process/continual-improvement-process] BS 8624 describes requirements for continual improvement and provides methods and examples of recognized techniques.
[src:continual-improvement-process/deductive-reasoning] Deductive reasoning contrasts with non-deductive or ampliative reasoning.
[src:continual-improvement-process/deductive-reasoning] For ampliative arguments, such as inductive or abductive arguments, the premises offer weaker support to their conclusion: they indicate that it is most likely, but they do not guarantee its truth.
[src:continual-improvement-process/deductive-reasoning] They make up for this drawback with their ability to provide genuinely new information (that is, information not already found in the premises), unlike deductive arguments.
[src:continual-improvement-process/deductive-reasoning] A branch of cognitive psychology, the psychology of reasoning, investigates the mental processes responsible for deductive reasoning.
[src:continual-improvement-process/deductive-reasoning] One of its topics concerns the factors determining whether people draw valid or invalid deductive inferences.
[src:continual-improvement-process/deductive-reasoning] One such factor is the form of the argument: for example, people draw valid inferences more successfully for arguments of the form modus ponens than of the form modus tollens.
[src:continual-improvement-process/deductive-reasoning] Another factor is the content of the arguments: people are more likely to believe that an argument is valid if the claim made in its conclusion is plausible.
[src:continual-improvement-process/deductive-reasoning] A general finding is that people tend to perform better for realistic and concrete cases than for abstract cases.
[src:continual-improvement-process/deductive-reasoning] Psychological theories of deductive reasoning aim to explain these findings by providing an account of the underlying psychological processes.
[src:continual-improvement-process/deductive-reasoning] *Mental logic theories* hold that deductive reasoning is a language-like process that happens through the manipulation of representations using rules of inference.
[src:continual-improvement-process/deductive-reasoning] *Mental model theories*, on the other hand, claim that deductive reasoning involves models of possible states of the world without the medium of language or rules of inference.
[src:continual-improvement-process/deductive-reasoning] According to *dual-process theories* of reasoning, there are two qualitatively different cognitive systems responsible for reasoning.
[src:continual-improvement-process/deductive-reasoning] The problem of deduction is relevant to various fields and issues.
[src:continual-improvement-process/deductive-reasoning] Epistemology tries to understand how justification is transferred from the belief in the premises to the belief in the conclusion in the process of deductive reasoning.
[src:continual-improvement-process/deductive-reasoning] Probability logic studies how the probability of the premises of an inference affects the probability of its conclusion.
[src:continual-improvement-process/deductive-reasoning] The controversial thesis of deductivism denies that there are other correct forms of inference besides deduction.
[src:continual-improvement-process/deductive-reasoning] Natural deduction is a type of proof system based on simple and self-evident rules of inference.
[src:continual-improvement-process/deductive-reasoning] In philosophy, the geometrical method is a way of philosophizing that starts from a small set of self-evident axioms and tries to build a comprehensive logical system using deductive reasoning.
[src:continual-improvement-process/deductive-reasoning] Deductive reasoning is the psychological process of drawing deductive inferences.
[src:continual-improvement-process/deductive-reasoning] An inference is a set of premises together with a conclusion.
[src:continual-improvement-process/deductive-reasoning] This psychological process starts from the premises and reasons to a conclusion based on and supported by these premises.
[src:continual-improvement-process/deductive-reasoning] If the reasoning was done correctly, it results in a valid deduction: the truth of the premises ensures the truth of the conclusion.
[src:continual-improvement-process/deductive-reasoning] For example, in the syllogistic argument "all frogs are amphibians; no cats are amphibians; therefore, no cats are frogs" the conclusion is true because its two premises are true.
[src:continual-improvement-process/deductive-reasoning] But even arguments with wrong premises can be deductively valid if they obey this principle, as in "all frogs are mammals; no cats are mammals; therefore, no cats are frogs".
[src:continual-improvement-process/deductive-reasoning] If the premises of a valid argument are true, then it is called a sound argument.
[src:continual-improvement-process/deductive-reasoning] The relation between the premises and the conclusion of a deductive argument is usually referred to as "logical consequence".
[src:continual-improvement-process/deductive-reasoning] According to Alfred Tarski, logical consequence has 3 essential features: it is necessary, formal, and knowable a priori.
[src:continual-improvement-process/deductive-reasoning] It is necessary in the sense that the premises of valid deductive arguments necessitate the conclusion: it is impossible for the premises to be true and the conclusion to be false, independent of any other circumstances.
[src:continual-improvement-process/deductive-reasoning] Logical consequence is formal in the sense that it depends only on the form or the syntax of the premises and the conclusion.
[src:continual-improvement-process/deductive-reasoning] This means that the validity of a particular argument does not depend on the specific contents of this argument.
[src:continual-improvement-process/deductive-reasoning] If it is valid, then any argument with the same logical form is also valid, no matter how different it is on the level of its contents.
[src:continual-improvement-process/deductive-reasoning] Logical consequence is knowable a priori in the sense that no empirical knowledge of the world is necessary to determine whether a deduction is valid.
[src:continual-improvement-process/deductive-reasoning] So it is not necessary to engage in any form of empirical investigation.
[src:continual-improvement-process/deductive-reasoning] Some logicians define deduction in terms of possible worlds: A deductive inference is valid if and only if, there is no possible world in which its conclusion is false while its premises are true.
[src:continual-improvement-process/deductive-reasoning] This means that there are no counterexamples: the conclusion is true in *all* such cases, not just in *most* cases.
[src:continual-improvement-process/deductive-reasoning] It has been argued against this and similar definitions that they fail to distinguish between valid and invalid deductive reasoning, i.e. they leave it open whether there are invalid deductive inferences and how to define them.
[src:continual-improvement-process/deductive-reasoning] Some authors define deductive reasoning in psychological terms in order to avoid this problem.
[src:continual-improvement-process/deductive-reasoning] According to Mark Vorobey, whether an argument is deductive depends on the psychological state of the person making the argument: "An argument is deductive if, and only if, the author of the argument believes that the truth of the premises necessitates (guarantees) the truth of the conclusion".
[src:continual-improvement-process/deductive-reasoning] A similar formulation holds that the speaker *claims* or *intends* that the premises offer deductive support for their conclusion.
[src:continual-improvement-process/deductive-reasoning] This is sometimes categorized as a *speaker-determined* definition of deduction since it depends also on the speaker whether the argument in question is deductive or not.
[src:continual-improvement-process/deductive-reasoning] For *speakerless* definitions, on the other hand, only the argument itself matters independent of the speaker.
[src:continual-improvement-process/deductive-reasoning] One advantage of this type of formulation is that it makes it possible to distinguish between good or valid and bad or invalid deductive arguments: the argument is good if the author's belief concerning the relation between the premises and the conclusion is true, otherwise it is bad.
[src:continual-improvement-process/deductive-reasoning] One consequence of this approach is that deductive arguments cannot be identified by the law of inference they use.
[src:continual-improvement-process/deductive-reasoning] For example, an argument of the form modus ponens may be non-deductive if the author's beliefs are sufficiently confused.
[src:continual-improvement-process/deductive-reasoning] That brings with it an important drawback of this definition: it is difficult to apply to concrete cases since the intentions of the author are usually not explicitly stated.
[src:continual-improvement-process/deductive-reasoning] Deductive reasoning is studied in logic, psychology, and the cognitive sciences.
[src:continual-improvement-process/deductive-reasoning] Some theorists emphasize in their definition the difference between these fields.
[src:continual-improvement-process/deductive-reasoning] On this view, psychology studies deductive reasoning as an empirical mental process, i.e. what happens when humans engage in reasoning.
[src:continual-improvement-process/deductive-reasoning] But the descriptive question of how actual reasoning happens is different from the normative question of how it *should* happen or what constitutes *correct* deductive reasoning, which is studied by logic.
[src:continual-improvement-process/deductive-reasoning] This is sometimes expressed by stating that, strictly speaking, logic does not study deductive reasoning but the deductive relation between premises and a conclusion known as logical consequence.
[src:continual-improvement-process/deductive-reasoning] But this distinction is not always precisely observed in the academic literature.
[src:continual-improvement-process/deductive-reasoning] One important aspect of this difference is that logic is not interested in whether the conclusion of an argument is sensible.
[src:continual-improvement-process/deductive-reasoning] So from the premise "the printer has ink" one may draw the unhelpful conclusion "the printer has ink and the printer has ink and the printer has ink", which has little relevance from a psychological point of view.
[src:continual-improvement-process/deductive-reasoning] Instead, actual reasoners usually try to remove redundant or irrelevant information and make the relevant information more explicit.
[src:continual-improvement-process/deductive-reasoning] The psychological study of deductive reasoning is also concerned with how good people are at drawing deductive inferences and with the factors determining their performance.
[src:continual-improvement-process/deductive-reasoning] Deductive inferences are found both in natural language and in formal logical systems, such as propositional logic.
[src:continual-improvement-process/deductive-reasoning] Deductive arguments differ from non-deductive arguments in that the truth of their premises ensures the truth of their conclusion.
[src:continual-improvement-process/deductive-reasoning] There are two important conceptions of what this exactly means.
[src:continual-improvement-process/deductive-reasoning] They are referred to as the syntactic and the semantic approach.
[src:continual-improvement-process/deductive-reasoning] According to the syntactic approach, whether an argument is deductively valid depends only on its form, syntax, or structure.
[src:continual-improvement-process/deductive-reasoning] Two arguments have the same form if they use the same logical vocabulary in the same arrangement, even if their contents differ.
[src:continual-improvement-process/deductive-reasoning] For example, the arguments "if it rains then the street will be wet; it rains; therefore, the street will be wet" and "if the meat is not cooled then it will spoil; the meat is not cooled; therefore, it will spoil" have the same logical form: they follow the modus ponens.
[src:continual-improvement-process/deductive-reasoning] Their form can be expressed more abstractly as "if A then B; A; therefore B" in order to make the common syntax explicit.
[src:continual-improvement-process/deductive-reasoning] There are various other valid logical forms or rules of inference, like modus tollens or the disjunction elimination.
[src:continual-improvement-process/deductive-reasoning] The syntactic approach then holds that an argument is deductively valid if and only if its conclusion can be deduced from its premises using a valid rule of inference.
[src:continual-improvement-process/deductive-reasoning] One difficulty for the syntactic approach is that it is usually necessary to express the argument in a formal language in order to assess whether it is valid.
[src:continual-improvement-process/deductive-reasoning] This often brings with it the difficulty of translating the natural language argument into a formal language, a process that comes with various problems of its own.
[src:continual-improvement-process/deductive-reasoning] Another difficulty is due to the fact that the syntactic approach depends on the distinction between formal and non-formal features.
[src:continual-improvement-process/deductive-reasoning] While there is a wide agreement concerning the paradigmatic cases, there are also various controversial cases where it is not clear how this distinction is to be drawn.
[src:continual-improvement-process/deductive-reasoning] The semantic approach suggests an alternative definition of deductive validity.
[src:continual-improvement-process/deductive-reasoning] It is based on the idea that the sentences constituting the premises and conclusions have to be interpreted in order to determine whether the argument is valid.
[src:continual-improvement-process/deductive-reasoning] This means that one ascribes semantic values to the expressions used in the sentences, such as the reference to an object for singular terms or to a truth-value for atomic sentences.
[src:continual-improvement-process/deductive-reasoning] The semantic approach is also referred to as the model-theoretic approach since the branch of mathematics known as model theory is often used to interpret these sentences.
[src:continual-improvement-process/deductive-reasoning] Usually, many different interpretations are possible, such as whether a singular term refers to one object or to another.
[src:continual-improvement-process/deductive-reasoning] According to the semantic approach, an argument is deductively valid if and only if there is no possible interpretation where its premises are true and its conclusion is false.
[src:continual-improvement-process/deductive-reasoning] Some objections to the semantic approach are based on the claim that the semantics of a language cannot be expressed in the same language, i.e. that a richer metalanguage is necessary.
[src:continual-improvement-process/deductive-reasoning] This would imply that the semantic approach cannot provide a universal account of deduction for language as an all-encompassing medium.
[src:continual-improvement-process/deductive-reasoning] Deductive reasoning usually happens by applying rules of inference.
[src:continual-improvement-process/deductive-reasoning] A rule of inference is a way or schema of drawing a conclusion from a set of premises.
[src:continual-improvement-process/deductive-reasoning] This happens usually based only on the logical form of the premises.
[src:continual-improvement-process/deductive-reasoning] A rule of inference is valid if, when applied to true premises, the conclusion cannot be false.
[src:continual-improvement-process/deductive-reasoning] A particular argument is valid if it follows a valid rule of inference.
[src:continual-improvement-process/deductive-reasoning] Deductive arguments that do not follow a valid rule of inference are called formal fallacies: the truth of their premises does not ensure the truth of their conclusion.
[src:continual-improvement-process/deductive-reasoning] In some cases, whether a rule of inference is valid depends on the logical system one is using.
[src:continual-improvement-process/deductive-reasoning] The dominant logical system is classical logic and the rules of inference listed here are all valid in classical logic.
[src:continual-improvement-process/deductive-reasoning] But so-called deviant logics provide a different account of which inferences are valid.
[src:continual-improvement-process/deductive-reasoning] For example, the rule of inference known as double negation elimination, i.e. that if a proposition is *not not true* then it is also *true*, is accepted in classical logic but rejected in intuitionistic logic.
[src:continual-improvement-process/deductive-reasoning] Modus ponens (also known as "affirming the antecedent" or "the law of detachment") is the primary deductive rule of inference.
[src:continual-improvement-process/deductive-reasoning] It applies to arguments that have as first premise a conditional statement ( $P\rightarrow Q$ ) and as second premise the antecedent ( P ) of the conditional statement.
[src:continual-improvement-process/deductive-reasoning] It obtains the consequent ( Q ) of the conditional statement as its conclusion.
[src:continual-improvement-process/deductive-reasoning] In this form of deductive reasoning, the consequent ( Q ) obtains as the conclusion from the premises of a conditional statement ( $P\rightarrow Q$ ) and its antecedent ( P ).
[src:continual-improvement-process/deductive-reasoning] However, the antecedent ( P ) cannot be similarly obtained as the conclusion from the premises of the conditional statement ( $P\rightarrow Q$ ) and the consequent ( Q ).
[src:continual-improvement-process/deductive-reasoning] Such an argument commits the logical fallacy of affirming the consequent.
[src:continual-improvement-process/deductive-reasoning] Modus tollens (also known as "the law of contrapositive") is a deductive rule of inference.
[src:continual-improvement-process/deductive-reasoning] It validates an argument that has as premises a conditional statement (formula) and the negation of the consequent ( $\lnot Q$ ) and as conclusion the negation of the antecedent ( $\lnot P$ ).
[src:continual-improvement-process/deductive-reasoning] In contrast to modus ponens, reasoning with modus tollens goes in the opposite direction to that of the conditional.
[src:continual-improvement-process/deductive-reasoning] A *hypothetical syllogism* is an inference that takes two conditional statements and forms a conclusion by combining the hypothesis of one statement with the conclusion of another.
[src:continual-improvement-process/deductive-reasoning] In there being a subformula in common between the two premises that does not occur in the consequence, this resembles syllogisms in term logic, although it differs in that this subformula is a proposition whereas in Aristotelian logic, this common element is a term and not a proposition.
[src:continual-improvement-process/deductive-reasoning] If it had rained, things would have gotten wet.
[src:continual-improvement-process/deductive-reasoning] Thus, if there had been a thunderstorm, things would have gotten wet.
[src:continual-improvement-process/deductive-reasoning] Various formal fallacies have been described.
[src:continual-improvement-process/deductive-reasoning] They are invalid forms of deductive reasoning.
[src:continual-improvement-process/deductive-reasoning] An additional aspect of them is that they appear to be valid on some occasions or on the first impression.
[src:continual-improvement-process/deductive-reasoning] They may thereby seduce people into accepting and committing them.
[src:continual-improvement-process/deductive-reasoning] One type of formal fallacy is affirming the consequent, as in "if John is a bachelor, then he is male; John is male; therefore, John is a bachelor".
[src:continual-improvement-process/deductive-reasoning] This is similar to the valid rule of inference named modus ponens, but the second premise and the conclusion are switched around, which is why it is invalid.
[src:continual-improvement-process/deductive-reasoning] A similar formal fallacy is denying the antecedent, as in "if Othello is a bachelor, then he is male; Othello is not a bachelor; therefore, Othello is not male".
[src:continual-improvement-process/deductive-reasoning] This is similar to the valid rule of inference called modus tollens, the difference being that the second premise and the conclusion are switched around.
[src:continual-improvement-process/deductive-reasoning] Other formal fallacies include affirming a disjunct, denying a conjunct, and the fallacy of the undistributed middle.
[src:continual-improvement-process/deductive-reasoning] All of them have in common that the truth of their premises does not ensure the truth of their conclusion.
[src:continual-improvement-process/deductive-reasoning] But it may still happen by coincidence that both the premises and the conclusion of formal fallacies are true.
[src:continual-improvement-process/deductive-reasoning] Rules of inferences are definitory rules: they determine whether an argument is deductively valid or not.
[src:continual-improvement-process/deductive-reasoning] But reasoners are usually not just interested in making any kind of valid argument.
[src:continual-improvement-process/deductive-reasoning] Instead, they often have a specific point or conclusion that they wish to prove or refute.
[src:continual-improvement-process/deductive-reasoning] So given a set of premises, they are faced with the problem of choosing the relevant rules of inference for their deduction to arrive at their intended conclusion.
[src:continual-improvement-process/deductive-reasoning] This issue belongs to the field of strategic rules: the question of which inferences need to be drawn to support one's conclusion.
[src:continual-improvement-process/deductive-reasoning] The distinction between definitory and strategic rules is not exclusive to logic: it is also found in various games.
[src:continual-improvement-process/deductive-reasoning] In chess, for example, the definitory rules state that bishops may only move diagonally while the strategic rules recommend that one should control the center and protect one's king if one intends to win.
[src:continual-improvement-process/deductive-reasoning] In this sense, definitory rules determine whether one plays chess or something else whereas strategic rules determine whether one is a good or a bad chess player.
[src:continual-improvement-process/deductive-reasoning] The same applies to deductive reasoning: to be an effective reasoner involves mastering both definitory and strategic rules.
[src:continual-improvement-process/deductive-reasoning] Deductive arguments are evaluated in terms of their *validity* and *soundness*.
[src:continual-improvement-process/deductive-reasoning] An argument is *valid* if it is impossible for its premises to be true while its conclusion is false.
[src:continual-improvement-process/deductive-reasoning] In other words, the conclusion must be true if the premises are true.
[src:continual-improvement-process/deductive-reasoning] An argument can be "valid" even if one or more of its premises are false.
[src:continual-improvement-process/deductive-reasoning] An argument is *sound* if it is *valid* and the premises are true.
[src:continual-improvement-process/deductive-reasoning] It is possible to have a deductive argument that is logically *valid* but is not *sound*.
[src:continual-improvement-process/deductive-reasoning] Fallacious arguments often take that form.
[src:continual-improvement-process/deductive-reasoning] The example's first premise is false – there are people who eat carrots who are not quarterbacks – but the conclusion would necessarily be true, if the premises were true.
[src:continual-improvement-process/deductive-reasoning] In other words, it is impossible for the premises to be true and the conclusion false.
[src:continual-improvement-process/deductive-reasoning] Therefore, the argument is "valid", but not "sound".
[src:continual-improvement-process/deductive-reasoning] False generalizations – such as "Everyone who eats carrots is a quarterback" – are often used to make unsound arguments.
[src:continual-improvement-process/deductive-reasoning] The fact that there are some people who eat carrots but are not quarterbacks proves that the argument is unsound.
[src:continual-improvement-process/deductive-reasoning] In this example, the first statement uses categorical reasoning, saying that all carrot-eaters are definitely quarterbacks.
[src:continual-improvement-process/deductive-reasoning] This theory of deductive reasoning – also known as term logic – was developed by Aristotle, but was superseded by propositional (sentential) logic and predicate logic.
[src:continual-improvement-process/deductive-reasoning] Deductive reasoning can be contrasted with inductive reasoning, in regards to validity and soundness.
[src:continual-improvement-process/deductive-reasoning] In cases of inductive reasoning, even though the premises are true and the argument is "valid", it is possible for the conclusion to be false (determined to be false with a counterexample or other means).
[src:continual-improvement-process/deductive-reasoning] Deductive reasoning is usually contrasted with non-deductive or ampliative reasoning.
[src:continual-improvement-process/deductive-reasoning] The hallmark of valid deductive inferences is that it is impossible for their premises to be true and their conclusion to be false.
[src:continual-improvement-process/deductive-reasoning] In this way, the premises provide the strongest possible support to their conclusion.
[src:continual-improvement-process/deductive-reasoning] The premises of ampliative inferences also support their conclusion.
[src:continual-improvement-process/deductive-reasoning] But this support is weaker: they are not necessarily truth-preserving.
[src:continual-improvement-process/deductive-reasoning] So even for correct ampliative arguments, it is possible that their premises are true and their conclusion is false.
[src:continual-improvement-process/deductive-reasoning] Two important forms of ampliative reasoning are inductive and abductive reasoning.
[src:continual-improvement-process/deductive-reasoning] Sometimes the term "inductive reasoning" is used in a very wide sense to cover all forms of ampliative reasoning.
[src:continual-improvement-process/deductive-reasoning] However, in a more strict usage, inductive reasoning is just one form of ampliative reasoning.
[src:continual-improvement-process/deductive-reasoning] In the narrow sense, inductive inferences are forms of statistical generalization.
[src:continual-improvement-process/deductive-reasoning] They are usually based on many individual observations that all show a certain pattern.
[src:continual-improvement-process/deductive-reasoning] These observations are then used to form a conclusion either about a yet unobserved entity or about a general law.
[src:continual-improvement-process/deductive-reasoning] For abductive inferences, the premises support the conclusion because the conclusion is the best explanation of why the premises are true.
[src:continual-improvement-process/deductive-reasoning] The support ampliative arguments provide for their conclusion comes in degrees: some ampliative arguments are stronger than others.
[src:continual-improvement-process/deductive-reasoning] This is often explained in terms of probability: the premises make it more likely that the conclusion is true.
[src:continual-improvement-process/deductive-reasoning] Strong ampliative arguments make their conclusion very likely, but not absolutely certain.
[src:continual-improvement-process/deductive-reasoning] An example of ampliative reasoning is the inference from the premise "every raven in a random sample of 3200 ravens is black" to the conclusion "all ravens are black": the extensive random sample makes the conclusion very likely, but it does not exclude that there are rare exceptions.
[src:continual-improvement-process/deductive-reasoning] In this sense, ampliative reasoning is defeasible: it may become necessary to retract an earlier conclusion upon receiving new related information.
[src:continual-improvement-process/deductive-reasoning] Ampliative reasoning is very common in everyday discourse and the sciences.
[src:continual-improvement-process/deductive-reasoning] An important drawback of deductive reasoning is that it does not lead to genuinely new information.
[src:continual-improvement-process/deductive-reasoning] This means that the conclusion only repeats information already found in the premises.
[src:continual-improvement-process/deductive-reasoning] Ampliative reasoning, on the other hand, goes beyond the premises by arriving at genuinely new information.
[src:continual-improvement-process/deductive-reasoning] One difficulty for this characterization is that it makes deductive reasoning appear useless: if deduction is uninformative, it is not clear why people would engage in it and study it.
[src:continual-improvement-process/deductive-reasoning] It has been suggested that this problem can be solved by distinguishing between surface and depth information.
[src:continual-improvement-process/deductive-reasoning] On this view, deductive reasoning is uninformative on the depth level, in contrast to ampliative reasoning.
[src:continual-improvement-process/deductive-reasoning] But it may still be valuable on the surface level by presenting the information in the premises in a new and sometimes surprising way.
[src:continual-improvement-process/deductive-reasoning] A popular misconception of the relation between deduction and induction identifies their difference on the level of particular and general claims.
[src:continual-improvement-process/deductive-reasoning] On this view, deductive inferences start from general premises and draw particular conclusions, while inductive inferences start from particular premises and draw general conclusions.
[src:continual-improvement-process/deductive-reasoning] This idea is often motivated by seeing deduction and induction as two inverse processes that complement each other: deduction is *top-down* while induction is *bottom-up*.
[src:continual-improvement-process/deductive-reasoning] But this is a misconception that does not reflect how valid deduction is defined in the field of logic: a deduction is valid if it is impossible for its premises to be true while its conclusion is false, independent of whether the premises or the conclusion are particular or general.
[src:continual-improvement-process/deductive-reasoning] Because of this, some deductive inferences have a general conclusion and some also have particular premises.
[src:continual-improvement-process/deductive-reasoning] A branch of cognitive psychology, the psychology of reasoning studies the psychological processes responsible for deductive reasoning.
[src:continual-improvement-process/deductive-reasoning] It is concerned, among other things, with how good people are at drawing valid deductive inferences.
[src:continual-improvement-process/deductive-reasoning] This includes the study of the factors affecting their performance, their tendency to commit fallacies, and the underlying biases involved.
[src:continual-improvement-process/deductive-reasoning] A notable finding in this field is that the type of deductive inference has a significant impact on whether the correct conclusion is drawn.
[src:continual-improvement-process/deductive-reasoning] In a meta-analysis of 65 studies, for example, 97% of the subjects evaluated modus ponens inferences correctly, while the success rate for modus tollens was only 72%.
[src:continual-improvement-process/deductive-reasoning] On the other hand, even some fallacies like affirming the consequent or denying the antecedent were regarded as valid arguments by the majority of the subjects.
[src:continual-improvement-process/deductive-reasoning] An important factor for these mistakes is whether the conclusion seems initially plausible: the more believable the conclusion is, the higher the chance that a subject will mistake a fallacy for a valid argument.
[src:continual-improvement-process/deductive-reasoning] An important bias is the *matching bias*, which is often illustrated using the Wason selection task.
[src:continual-improvement-process/deductive-reasoning] In an often-cited experiment by Peter Wason, four cards are presented to the participant.
[src:continual-improvement-process/deductive-reasoning] In one case, the visible sides show the symbols D, K, 5, and 7 on the different cards.
[src:continual-improvement-process/deductive-reasoning] The participant is told that every card has a letter on one side and a number on the other side, and that "[e]very card which has a D on one side has a 5 on the other side".
[src:continual-improvement-process/deductive-reasoning] Their task is to identify which cards need to be turned around in order to confirm or refute this conditional claim.
[src:continual-improvement-process/deductive-reasoning] The correct answer, only given by about 10%, is the cards D and 7.
[src:continual-improvement-process/deductive-reasoning] Many select card 5 instead, even though the conditional claim does not involve any requirements on what symbols can be found on the opposite side of card 5.
[src:continual-improvement-process/deductive-reasoning] In this case, 74% of the participants identified correctly that the cards "drinking a beer" and "16 years of age" have to be turned around.
[src:continual-improvement-process/deductive-reasoning] These findings suggest that the deductive reasoning ability is heavily influenced by the content of the involved claims and not just by the abstract logical form of the task: the more realistic and concrete the cases are, the better the subjects tend to perform.
[src:continual-improvement-process/deductive-reasoning] Another bias is called the "negative conclusion bias", which happens when one of the premises has the form of a negative material conditional, as in "If the card does not have an A on the left, then it has a 3 on the right.
[src:continual-improvement-process/deductive-reasoning] The card does not have a 3 on the right.
[src:continual-improvement-process/deductive-reasoning] Therefore, the card has an A on the left".
[src:continual-improvement-process/deductive-reasoning] The increased tendency to misjudge the validity of this type of argument is not present for positive material conditionals, as in "If the card has an A on the left, then it has a 3 on the right.
[src:continual-improvement-process/deductive-reasoning] Therefore, the card does not have an A on the left".
[src:continual-improvement-process/deductive-reasoning] Various psychological theories of deductive reasoning have been proposed.
[src:continual-improvement-process/deductive-reasoning] These theories aim to explain how deductive reasoning works in relation to the underlying psychological processes responsible.
[src:continual-improvement-process/deductive-reasoning] They are often used to explain the empirical findings, such as why human reasoners are more susceptible to some types of fallacies than to others.
[src:continual-improvement-process/deductive-reasoning] An important distinction is between *mental logic theories*, sometimes also referred to as *rule theories*, and *mental model theories*.
[src:continual-improvement-process/deductive-reasoning] *Mental logic theories* see deductive reasoning as a language-like process that happens through the manipulation of representations.
[src:continual-improvement-process/deductive-reasoning] This is done by applying syntactic rules of inference in a way very similar to how systems of natural deduction transform their premises to arrive at a conclusion.
[src:continual-improvement-process/deductive-reasoning] On this view, some deductions are simpler than others since they involve fewer inferential steps.
[src:continual-improvement-process/deductive-reasoning] In such cases, the additional cognitive labor makes the inferences more open to error.
[src:continual-improvement-process/deductive-reasoning] Both mental logic theories and mental model theories assume that there is one general-purpose reasoning mechanism that applies to all forms of deductive reasoning.
[src:continual-improvement-process/deductive-reasoning] But there are also alternative accounts that posit various different special-purpose reasoning mechanisms for different contents and contexts.
[src:continual-improvement-process/deductive-reasoning] In this sense, it has been claimed that humans possess a special mechanism for permissions and obligations, specifically for detecting cheating in social exchanges.
[src:continual-improvement-process/deductive-reasoning] This can be used to explain why humans are often more successful in drawing valid inferences if the contents involve human behavior in relation to social norms.
[src:continual-improvement-process/deductive-reasoning] Another example is the so-called dual-process theory.
[src:continual-improvement-process/deductive-reasoning] This theory posits that there are two distinct cognitive systems responsible for reasoning.
[src:continual-improvement-process/deductive-reasoning] Their interrelation can be used to explain commonly observed biases in deductive reasoning.
[src:continual-improvement-process/deductive-reasoning] System 1 is the older system in terms of evolution.
[src:continual-improvement-process/deductive-reasoning] It is based on associative learning and happens fast and automatically without demanding many cognitive resources.
[src:continual-improvement-process/deductive-reasoning] System 2, on the other hand, is of more recent evolutionary origin.
[src:continual-improvement-process/deductive-reasoning] It is slow and cognitively demanding, but also more flexible and under deliberate control.
[src:continual-improvement-process/deductive-reasoning] The dual-process theory posits that system 1 is the default system guiding most of our everyday reasoning in a pragmatic way.
[src:continual-improvement-process/deductive-reasoning] But for particularly difficult problems on the logical level, system 2 is employed.
[src:continual-improvement-process/deductive-reasoning] System 2 is mostly responsible for deductive reasoning.
[src:continual-improvement-process/deductive-reasoning] The ability of deductive reasoning is an important aspect of intelligence and many tests of intelligence include problems that call for deductive inferences.
[src:continual-improvement-process/deductive-reasoning] Because of this relation to intelligence, deduction is highly relevant to psychology and the cognitive sciences.
[src:continual-improvement-process/deductive-reasoning] But the subject of deductive reasoning is also pertinent to the computer sciences, for example, in the creation of artificial intelligence.
[src:continual-improvement-process/deductive-reasoning] Deductive reasoning plays an important role in epistemology.
[src:continual-improvement-process/deductive-reasoning] Epistemology is concerned with the question of justification, i.e. to point out which beliefs are justified and why.
[src:continual-improvement-process/deductive-reasoning] Deductive inferences are able to transfer the justification of the premises onto the conclusion.
[src:continual-improvement-process/deductive-reasoning] So while logic is interested in the truth-preserving nature of deduction, epistemology is interested in the justification-preserving nature of deduction.
[src:continual-improvement-process/deductive-reasoning] There are different theories trying to explain why deductive reasoning is justification-preserving.
[src:continual-improvement-process/deductive-reasoning] According to reliabilism, this is the case because deductions are truth-preserving: they are reliable processes that ensure a true conclusion given the premises are true.
[src:continual-improvement-process/deductive-reasoning] Some theorists hold that the thinker has to have explicit awareness of the truth-preserving nature of the inference for the justification to be transferred from the premises to the conclusion.
[src:continual-improvement-process/deductive-reasoning] One consequence of such a view is that, for young children, this deductive transference does not take place since they lack this specific awareness.
[src:continual-improvement-process/deductive-reasoning] Probability logic is interested in how the probability of the premises of an argument affects the probability of its conclusion.
[src:continual-improvement-process/deductive-reasoning] It differs from classical logic, which assumes that propositions are either true or false but does not take into consideration the probability or certainty that a proposition is true or false.
[src:continual-improvement-process/deductive-reasoning] Aristotle, a Greek philosopher, started documenting deductive reasoning in the 4th century BC.
[src:continual-improvement-process/deductive-reasoning] René Descartes, in his book Discourse on Method, refined the idea for the Scientific Revolution.
[src:continual-improvement-process/deductive-reasoning] Developing four rules to follow for proving an idea deductively, Descartes laid the foundation for the deductive portion of the scientific method.
[src:continual-improvement-process/deductive-reasoning] Descartes' background in geometry and mathematics influenced his ideas on the truth and reasoning, causing him to develop a system of general reasoning now used for most mathematical reasoning.
[src:continual-improvement-process/deductive-reasoning] Similar to postulates, Descartes believed that ideas could be self-evident and that reasoning alone must prove that observations are reliable.
[src:continual-improvement-process/deductive-reasoning] These ideas also lay the foundations for the ideas of rationalism.
[src:continual-improvement-process/deductive-reasoning] Deductivism is a philosophical position that gives primacy to deductive reasoning or arguments over their non-deductive counterparts.
[src:continual-improvement-process/deductive-reasoning] It is often understood as the evaluative claim that only deductive inferences are *good* or *correct* inferences.
[src:continual-improvement-process/deductive-reasoning] This theory would have wide-reaching consequences for various fields since it implies that the rules of deduction are "the only acceptable standard of evidence".
[src:continual-improvement-process/deductive-reasoning] This way, the rationality or correctness of the different forms of inductive reasoning is denied.
[src:continual-improvement-process/deductive-reasoning] Some forms of deductivism express this in terms of degrees of reasonableness or probability.
[src:continual-improvement-process/deductive-reasoning] Inductive inferences are usually seen as providing a certain degree of support for their conclusion: they make it more likely that their conclusion is true.
[src:continual-improvement-process/deductive-reasoning] Deductivism states that such inferences are not rational: the premises either ensure their conclusion, as in deductive reasoning, or they do not provide any support at all.
[src:continual-improvement-process/deductive-reasoning] One motivation for deductivism is the problem of induction introduced by David Hume.
[src:continual-improvement-process/deductive-reasoning] It consists in the challenge of explaining how or whether inductive inferences based on past experiences support conclusions about future events.
[src:continual-improvement-process/deductive-reasoning] For example, a chicken comes to expect, based on all its past experiences, that the person entering its coop is going to feed it, until one day the person "at last wrings its neck instead".
[src:continual-improvement-process/deductive-reasoning] According to Karl Popper's falsificationism, deductive reasoning alone is sufficient.
[src:continual-improvement-process/deductive-reasoning] This is due to its truth-preserving nature: a theory can be falsified if one of its deductive consequences is false.
[src:continual-improvement-process/deductive-reasoning] So while inductive reasoning does not offer positive evidence for a theory, the theory still remains a viable competitor until falsified by empirical observation.
[src:continual-improvement-process/deductive-reasoning] In this sense, deduction alone is sufficient for discriminating between competing hypotheses about what is the case.
[src:continual-improvement-process/deductive-reasoning] Hypothetico-deductivism is a closely related scientific method, according to which science progresses by formulating hypotheses and then aims to falsify them by trying to make observations that run counter to their deductive consequences.
[src:continual-improvement-process/deductive-reasoning] The term "natural deduction" refers to a class of proof systems based on self-evident rules of inference.
[src:continual-improvement-process/deductive-reasoning] The first systems of natural deduction were developed by Gerhard Gentzen and Stanislaw Jaskowski in the 1930s.
[src:continual-improvement-process/deductive-reasoning] The core motivation was to give a simple presentation of deductive reasoning that closely mirrors how reasoning actually takes place.
[src:continual-improvement-process/deductive-reasoning] In this sense, natural deduction stands in contrast to other less intuitive proof systems, such as Hilbert-style deductive systems, which employ axiom schemes to express logical truths.
[src:continual-improvement-process/deductive-reasoning] Natural deduction, on the other hand, avoids axioms schemes by including many different rules of inference that can be used to formulate proofs.
[src:continual-improvement-process/deductive-reasoning] These rules of inference express how logical constants behave.
[src:continual-improvement-process/deductive-reasoning] They are often divided into introduction rules and elimination rules.
[src:continual-improvement-process/deductive-reasoning] Introduction rules specify under which conditions a logical constant may be introduced into a new sentence of the proof.
[src:continual-improvement-process/deductive-reasoning] For example, the introduction rule for the logical constant " $\land$ " (and) is " ${\frac {A,B}{(A\land B)}}$ ".
[src:continual-improvement-process/deductive-reasoning] It expresses that, given the premises " A " and " B " individually, one may draw the conclusion " $A\land B$ " and thereby include it in one's proof.
[src:continual-improvement-process/deductive-reasoning] This way, the symbol " $\land$ " is introduced into the proof.
[src:continual-improvement-process/deductive-reasoning] The removal of this symbol is governed by other rules of inference, such as the elimination rule " ${\frac {(A\land B)}{A}}$ ", which states that one may deduce the sentence " A " from the premise " $(A\land B)$ ".
[src:continual-improvement-process/deductive-reasoning] Similar introduction and elimination rules are given for other logical constants, such as the propositional operator " $\lnot$ ", the propositional connectives " $\lor$ " and " $\rightarrow$ ", and the quantifiers " $\exists$ " and " $\forall$ ".
[src:continual-improvement-process/deductive-reasoning] The focus on rules of inferences instead of axiom schemes is an important feature of natural deduction.
[src:continual-improvement-process/deductive-reasoning] But there is no general agreement on how natural deduction is to be defined.
[src:continual-improvement-process/deductive-reasoning] Some theorists hold that all proof systems with this feature are forms of natural deduction.
[src:continual-improvement-process/deductive-reasoning] This would include various forms of sequent calculi or tableau calculi.
[src:continual-improvement-process/deductive-reasoning] But other theorists use the term in a more narrow sense, for example, to refer to the proof systems developed by Gentzen and Jaskowski.
[src:continual-improvement-process/deductive-reasoning] Because of its simplicity, natural deduction is often used for teaching logic to students.
[src:continual-improvement-process/deductive-reasoning] The geometrical method is a method of philosophy based on deductive reasoning.
[src:continual-improvement-process/deductive-reasoning] It starts from a small set of self-evident axioms and tries to build a comprehensive logical system based only on deductive inferences from these first axioms.
[src:continual-improvement-process/deductive-reasoning] It was initially formulated by Baruch Spinoza and came to prominence in various rationalist philosophical systems in the modern era.
[src:continual-improvement-process/deductive-reasoning] It gets its name from the forms of mathematical demonstration found in traditional geometry, which are usually based on axioms, definitions, and inferred theorems.
[src:continual-improvement-process/deductive-reasoning] An important motivation of the geometrical method is to repudiate philosophical skepticism by grounding one's philosophical system on absolutely certain axioms.
[src:continual-improvement-process/deductive-reasoning] Deductive reasoning is central to this endeavor because of its necessarily truth-preserving nature.
[src:continual-improvement-process/deductive-reasoning] This way, the certainty initially invested only in the axioms is transferred to all parts of the philosophical system.
[src:continual-improvement-process/deductive-reasoning] One recurrent criticism of philosophical systems build using the geometrical method is that their initial axioms are not as self-evident or certain as their defenders proclaim.
[src:continual-improvement-process/deductive-reasoning] This problem lies beyond the deductive reasoning itself, which only ensures that the conclusion is true if the premises are true, but not that the premises themselves are true.
[src:continual-improvement-process/deductive-reasoning] For example, Spinoza's philosophical system has been criticized this way based on objections raised against the causal axiom, i.e. that "the knowledge of an effect depends on and involves knowledge of its cause".
[src:continual-improvement-process/deductive-reasoning] A different criticism targets not the premises but the reasoning itself, which may at times implicitly assume premises that are themselves not self-evident.
[src:continual-improvement-process/eco-management-and-audit-scheme] Although EMAS is an official EU Regulation, it is binding only for organisations which voluntarily decide to implement the scheme.
[src:continual-improvement-process/eco-management-and-audit-scheme] Because of its additional requirements, EMAS is known as the premium instrument for environmental management.
[src:continual-improvement-process/eco-management-and-audit-scheme] Environmental policy: definition of the organisation's overarching environmental objectives; commitment to continuous improvement of environmental performance.
[src:continual-improvement-process/eco-management-and-audit-scheme] Environmental program: description of measures, responsibilities and means to achieve environmental objectives and targets.
[src:continual-improvement-process/eco-management-and-audit-scheme] Environmental audit: systematic, documented, periodic and objective evaluation of the organisation's environmental performance, management system and processes designed to protect the environment, conducted by internal auditor(s).
[src:continual-improvement-process/eco-management-and-audit-scheme] The Eco-Management and Audit Scheme provides core indicators or key performance indicators (KPIs) with which registered organisations can measure their environmental performance and monitor their continual environmental improvement against set targets.
[src:continual-improvement-process/eco-management-and-audit-scheme] Entered into force in January 2010, EMAS III requires registered organisations to report on key performance indicators in six key environmental areas.
[src:continual-improvement-process/eco-management-and-audit-scheme] The indicators focus on direct environmental aspects and apply to all EMAS registered organisations.
[src:continual-improvement-process/eco-management-and-audit-scheme] The indicator En1 is a measure of the energy consumed, e.g. to produce a certain product.
[src:continual-improvement-process/eco-management-and-audit-scheme] By applying the indicator, organisations can identify energy "hot spots", assess possible improvement measures and benchmark their production processes against similar organisations.
[src:continual-improvement-process/eco-management-and-audit-scheme] Through the application of En2, organisations can see how climate-friendly their energy use is.
[src:continual-improvement-process/eco-management-and-audit-scheme] The indicator is useful for identifying the most important materials used and monitoring the effectiveness of improvement measures.
[src:continual-improvement-process/eco-management-and-audit-scheme] The indicator enables organisations to assess the success of the measures taken to reduce water consumption.
[src:continual-improvement-process/eco-management-and-audit-scheme] Hazardous wastes cause harmful environmental effects.
[src:continual-improvement-process/eco-management-and-audit-scheme] As a result, the EMAS Regulation is clear on the fact that hazardous waste has to be reported under a specific indicator.
[src:continual-improvement-process/eco-management-and-audit-scheme] By using the indicator, organisations can start monitoring their impact on ecosystems or habitats, through their land use.
[src:continual-improvement-process/eco-management-and-audit-scheme] Greenhouse gas (GHG) emissions of an organisation indicate an organisation's impact on the climate.
[src:continual-improvement-process/eco-management-and-audit-scheme] The indicator does not only focus on carbon dioxide emissions but also on other GHGs (see list above).
[src:continual-improvement-process/eco-management-and-audit-scheme] The indicator requires an organisation to report on several air emissions (see list above).
[src:continual-improvement-process/eco-management-and-audit-scheme] Using this indicator gives an organisation a thorough understanding of its impact on air quality.
[src:continual-improvement-process/eco-management-and-audit-scheme] All organisations listed in the EMAS Register run an environmental management system according to the EMAS requirements.
[src:continual-improvement-process/eco-management-and-audit-scheme] Because ISO 14001 is an integral part of EMAS, these organisations automatically comply with the requirements that the international standard demands as well.
[src:continual-improvement-process/eco-management-and-audit-scheme] However, EMAS registered organisations fulfill requirements that go beyond the scope of ISO 14001.
[src:continual-improvement-process/eco-management-and-audit-scheme] EMAS is a comprehensive and demanding premium label, whose implementation requires some financial and personnel resources.
[src:continual-improvement-process/eco-management-and-audit-scheme] In return, EMAS provides organisations with many advantages that can easily outweigh these costs.
[src:continual-improvement-process/eco-management-and-audit-scheme] As EMAS is tailored to individual performance improvements, each organisation has to consider different environmental and economic factors.
[src:continual-improvement-process/eco-management-and-audit-scheme] Given the heterogeneity of registered organisations, calculating average benefits and costs of EMAS is nearly unfeasible.
[src:continual-improvement-process/eco-management-and-audit-scheme] The financial benefits of an EMAS registered organisation can differ per country.
[src:continual-improvement-process/eco-management-and-audit-scheme] For example, some countries offer substantial reductions of waste fees, lower permitting costs, faster licensing procedures, etc.
[src:continual-improvement-process/eco-management-and-audit-scheme] Nevertheless, several studies have been undertaken to provide reference points on the benefits and costs.
[src:continual-improvement-process/eco-management-and-audit-scheme] In 2009, the European Commission published the Study on the Costs and Benefits of EMAS to Registered Organisations.
[src:continual-improvement-process/eco-management-and-audit-scheme] The results of this study are summarised in a factsheet.
[src:continual-improvement-process/eco-management-and-audit-scheme] The EMAS Awards praise efforts on environmental protection made by EMAS registered organisations.
[src:continual-improvement-process/eco-management-and-audit-scheme] The European Commission has handed out these awards every year since 2005.
[src:continual-improvement-process/eco-management-and-audit-scheme] EMAS Awards in environmental management are handed out annually to companies and public authorities in six categories.
[src:continual-improvement-process/eco-management-and-audit-scheme] EMAS Awards have a different focus every year.
[src:continual-improvement-process/eco-management-and-audit-scheme] Each year, the EMAS Awards winners are cited for their achievements in a specific area of their environmental performance.
[src:continual-improvement-process/eco-management-and-audit-scheme] Past themes have encompassed a variety of topics, including resource efficiency and waste management.
[src:continual-improvement-process/eco-management-and-audit-scheme] The theme of the 2011 EMAS Awards is *Stakeholder involvement leading to continuous improvement*.
[src:continual-improvement-process/eco-management-and-audit-scheme] The first EMAS Regulation (EMAS I) was adopted in 1993 and became operational in 1995.
[src:continual-improvement-process/eco-management-and-audit-scheme] It was originally restricted to companies in industrial sectors.
[src:continual-improvement-process/eco-management-and-audit-scheme] With the first revision of the EMAS Regulation in 2001 (EMAS II), the scheme opened to all economic sectors including public and private services.
[src:continual-improvement-process/eco-management-and-audit-scheme] The latest revision of EMAS came into effect on 11 January 2010 (EMAS III).
[src:continual-improvement-process/eco-management-and-audit-scheme] With the introduction of EMAS III, the scheme is globally applicable and no longer limited to EU Member States.
[src:continual-improvement-process/eco-management-and-audit-scheme] With EMAS III the EU also introduced obligatory Key Performance Indicators (KPI) in order to harmonize reporting on environmental performance.
[src:continual-improvement-process/eco-management-and-audit-scheme] The number of EMAS registered organisations increased from 2,140 in 1997 to 4,659 in 2011.
[src:continual-improvement-process/effectiveness] The origin of the word *effective* stems from the Latin word *effectīvus*, which means "creative, productive, or effective".
[src:continual-improvement-process/effectiveness] It surfaced in Middle English between 1300 and 1400 AD.
[src:continual-improvement-process/effectiveness] In mathematics and logic, *effective* is used to describe metalogical methods that fit the criteria of an effective procedure.
[src:continual-improvement-process/effectiveness] In group theory, a group element acts *effectively* (or *faithfully*) on a point, if that point is not fixed by the action.
[src:continual-improvement-process/effectiveness] In physics, an effective theory is, similar to a phenomenological theory, a framework intended to explain certain (observed) effects without the claim that the theory correctly models the underlying (unobserved) processes.
[src:continual-improvement-process/effectiveness] In heat transfer, *effectiveness* is a measure of the performance of a heat exchanger when using the NTU method.
[src:continual-improvement-process/effectiveness] In medicine, effectiveness relates to how well a treatment works in practice, especially as shown in pragmatic clinical trials, as opposed to efficacy, which measures how well it works in explanatory clinical trials or research laboratory studies.
[src:continual-improvement-process/effectiveness] In management, effectiveness relates to *getting the right things done*.
[src:continual-improvement-process/effectiveness] Peter Drucker reminds his readers that "effectiveness *can* and *must* be learned".
[src:continual-improvement-process/effectiveness] The term "institutional effectiveness" has been widely adopted within higher education settings to assess "how well an institution is achieving its mission and goals".
[src:continual-improvement-process/effectiveness] For example, Utica University in New York State holds that "an effective institution is characterized by a clearly defined mission that articulates who it serves, what it aspires to be, and what it values.
[src:continual-improvement-process/effectiveness] Likewise, an effective institution has clear goals that are broadly communicated to its stakeholders".
[src:continual-improvement-process/effectiveness] Pope Francis adopts the same term in a critique of governmental effectiveness when he refers to "a number of countries [with] a relatively low level of institutional effectiveness", which leads to "greater problems for their people while benefiting those who profit from this situation".
[src:continual-improvement-process/effectiveness] He refers, for example, to countries whose laws are "well written" but not effectively enforced.
[src:continual-improvement-process/effectiveness] In human–computer interaction, effectiveness is defined as "the accuracy and completeness of users' tasks while using a system".
[src:continual-improvement-process/effectiveness] Efficacy, efficiency, and effectivity are terms that can, in some cases, be interchangeable with the term effectiveness.
[src:continual-improvement-process/effectiveness] The word *effective* is sometimes used in a quantitative way, "being very effective or not very effective".
[src:continual-improvement-process/effectiveness] However, neither "effectiveness", nor "effectively", inform about the direction (positive or negative) or gives a comparison to a standard of the given effect.
[src:continual-improvement-process/effectiveness] Efficacy, on the other hand, is the extent to which a desired effect is achieved; the ability to produce a desired amount of the desired effect, or the success in achieving a given goal.
[src:continual-improvement-process/effectiveness] Contrary to the term efficiency, the focus of efficacy is the achievement as such, not the resources spent in achieving the desired effect.
[src:continual-improvement-process/effectiveness] Therefore, what is effective is not necessarily efficacious, and what is efficacious is not necessarily efficient.
[src:continual-improvement-process/effectiveness] Other synonyms for effectiveness include: clout, capability, success, weight, performance.
[src:continual-improvement-process/effectiveness] Antonyms for effectiveness include: uselessness, ineffectiveness.
[src:continual-improvement-process/effectiveness] Simply stated, effective means achieving an effect, and efficient means getting a task or job done it with little waste.
[src:continual-improvement-process/effectiveness] To illustrate: suppose, you build 10 houses, very fast and cheap (efficient), but no one buy them.
[src:continual-improvement-process/effectiveness] In contrary to building 5 houses same budget and time as 10 houses but you get all 5 sold and the buyers are happy (effective).
[src:continual-improvement-process/effectiveness] You get the desired result selling your houses and happy customers (effect).
[src:continual-improvement-process/efficiency] In more mathematical or scientific terms, it signifies the level of performance that uses the least amount of inputs to achieve the highest amount of output.
[src:continual-improvement-process/efficiency] It often specifically comprises the capability of a specific application of effort to produce a specific outcome with a minimum amount or quantity of waste, expense, or unnecessary effort.
[src:continual-improvement-process/efficiency] Efficiency refers to very different inputs and outputs in different fields and industries.
[src:continual-improvement-process/efficiency] In 2019, the European Commission said: "Resource efficiency means using the Earth's limited resources in a sustainable procent manner while minimising impacts on the environment.
[src:continual-improvement-process/efficiency] Writer Deborah Stone notes that efficiency is "not a goal in itself.
[src:continual-improvement-process/efficiency] Efficiency is very often confused with effectiveness.
[src:continual-improvement-process/efficiency] In general, efficiency is a measurable concept, quantitatively determined by the ratio of useful output to total useful input.
[src:continual-improvement-process/efficiency] Effectiveness is the simpler concept of being able to achieve a desired result, which can be expressed quantitatively but does not usually require more complicated mathematics than addition.
[src:continual-improvement-process/efficiency] Efficiency can often be expressed as a percentage of the result that could ideally be expected, for example if no energy were lost due to friction or other causes, in which case 100% of fuel or other input would be used to produce the desired result.
[src:continual-improvement-process/efficiency] In some cases efficiency can be indirectly quantified with impulse.
[src:continual-improvement-process/efficiency] A common but confusing way of distiguishing between efficiency and effectiveness is the saying "Efficiency is doing things right, while effectiveness is doing the right things".
[src:continual-improvement-process/efficiency] This saying indirectly emphasizes that the selection of objectives of a production process is just as important as the quality of that process.
[src:continual-improvement-process/efficiency] This saying popular in business, however, obscures the more common sense of "effectiveness", which would/should produce the following mnemonic: "Efficiency is doing things right; effectiveness is getting things done".
[src:continual-improvement-process/efficiency] Similarly, a company can achieve effectiveness, for example large production numbers, through inefficient processes if it can afford to use more energy per product, for example if energy prices or labor costs or both are lower than for its competitors.
[src:continual-improvement-process/efficiency] Productive inefficiency, resource-market inefficiency, and X-inefficiency might be analyzed using data envelopment analysis and similar methods.
[src:continual-improvement-process/efficiency] Efficiency is often measured as the ratio of useful output to total input, which can be expressed with the mathematical formula *r*=*P*/*C*, where *P* is the amount of useful output ("product") produced per the amount *C* ("cost") of resources consumed.
[src:continual-improvement-process/efficiency] This may correspond to a percentage if products and consumables are quantified in compatible units, and if consumables are transformed into products via a conservative process.
[src:continual-improvement-process/efficiency] For example, in the analysis of the energy conversion efficiency of heat engines in thermodynamics, the product *P* may be the amount of useful work output, while the consumable *C* is the amount of high-temperature heat input.
[src:continual-improvement-process/efficiency] Due to the conservation of energy, *P* can never be greater than *C*, and so the efficiency *r* is never greater than 100% (and in fact must be even less at finite temperatures).
